    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1960-09-19T11:48:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1960-09-19T11:48:00-05:00" n="171"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d171">
                <head>171. Telegram From the <gloss type="from">Department of State</gloss> to the
                        <gloss type="to">Mission at the United Nations</gloss>
                    <note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d171fn1">Source: Department of State, Central
                        Files, 320/9–1960. Top Secret; <gloss target="#t_NIACT1">Niact</gloss>; Eyes
                        Only. Drafted by <persName corresp="#p_BWCJ1">Burdett</persName> on
                        September 18; cleared by <persName corresp="#p_MLT1">Merchant</persName>,
                            <persName corresp="#p_BCE2">Bohlen</persName>, <persName
                            corresp="#p_SWJJ1">Stoessel</persName>, <persName corresp="#p_KFD1"
                            >Kohler</persName>, and <persName corresp="#p_KMV1">Krebs</persName>;
                        and approved by <persName corresp="#p_BWCJ1">Burdett</persName> who signed
                        for Herter. Sent also priority eyes only to <persName corresp="#p_WJJ2"
                            >Wadsworth</persName> and to Barbour, Minister of the Embassy in
                        London.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1960-09-19T12:48:00-04:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">September 19, 1960—12:48 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>433. Secretary and <persName corresp="#p_DHSAF1">Lord Home</persName> agreed on
                    following re strategy and tactics at General Assembly at meeting September
                        18.<note n="2" xml:id="d171fn2">A memorandum of this conversation is <hi
                            rend="italic">ibid</hi>., 320/9–1860.</note>
                </p>
                <list>
                    <label>1.</label>
                    <item>Useful for <persName corresp="#p_MHS2">Macmillan</persName> to come over
                        during week of September 26 and speak perhaps on September 30 or October
                        3.</item>
                    <label>2.</label>
                    <item>
                        <persName corresp="#p_MHS2">Macmillan</persName>–<persName corresp="#p_KNS2"
                            >Khrushchev</persName> meeting in US would not necessarily cause
                        difficulties with American public opinion if properly presented.</item>
                    <label>3.</label>
                    <item>Useful for <persName corresp="#p_MSRG1">Menzies</persName> to come over
                        and answer <persName corresp="#p_KNS2">Khrushchev</persName> at earlier date
                        than <persName corresp="#p_MHS2">Macmillan</persName>. <persName
                            corresp="#p_DHSAF1">Lord Home</persName> will ask <persName
                            corresp="#p_MHS2">Macmillan</persName> to see what he can do to
                        stimulate <persName corresp="#p_MSRG1">Menzies</persName>’
                        attendance.</item>
                    <label>4.</label>
                    <item>Might be useful for <persName corresp="#p_DJG1">Diefenbaker</persName> and
                            <persName corresp="#p_KMA1">Ayub</persName> to attend and also to answer
                            <persName corresp="#p_KNS2">Khrushchev</persName> earlier than <persName
                            corresp="#p_MHS2">Macmillan</persName>. However, <persName
                            corresp="#p_KMA1">Ayub</persName> already in exposed position and might
                        have domestic problems.</item>
                    <label>5.</label>
                    <item>Closest liaison between US-<gloss target="#t_UK1">UK</gloss> Delegations
                        in <gloss target="#t_NY1">NY</gloss> is essential. On publicity aspects
                            Glass<note n="3" xml:id="d171fn3">Presumably Leslie Charles Glass,
                            Director General of British Information Services in the United
                            States.</note> and <persName corresp="#p_BAH3">Berding</persName> should
                        concert in <gloss target="#t_NY1">NY</gloss> on Monday.</item>
                    <pb facs="0364" n="334" xml:id="pg_334"/>
                    <label>6.</label>
                    <item>Two Delegations should consult Monday regarding specific tactics and
                        publicity by which time <persName corresp="#p_KNS2">Khrushchev</persName>
                        may have tipped his hand.<note n="4" xml:id="d171fn4">No record of this
                            meeting has been found.</note>
                    </item>
                    <label>7.</label>
                    <item>Desirable terminate special General Assembly by Monday; not desirable for
                        special General Assembly and regular General Assembly to run
                        simultaneously.</item>
                    <label>8.</label>
                    <item>US and <gloss target="#t_UK1">UK</gloss> should start lobbying immediately
                        in General Committee to forestall any Soviet effort to obtain agreement to
                        sessions of Committee One, possibly on disarmament, concurrently with
                        general debate.</item>
                    <label>9.</label>
                    <item>If <persName corresp="#p_KNS2">Khrushchev</persName> introduces resolution
                        on disarmament US and <gloss target="#t_UK1">UK</gloss> should consult
                        together immediately on whether to move to refer matter to Committee of
                        Ten.</item>
                    <label>10.</label>
                    <item>Hold in abeyance decision on stand to be taken if considerable support
                        develops for enlargement of Committee of Ten.</item>
                    <label>11.</label>
                    <item>Experts to draft on contingency basis possible resolution on Germany and
                        Berlin for introduction in Security Council. Difficulties with French
                        anticipated.</item>
                </list>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="strong">Herter</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
